# User and Project Rule


- Assume the project requires maximum execution accuracy, strict adherence to user requirements, and complete backward traceability from input to output.
- Prefer terminal commands over GUI actions when terminal execution is available, safer, and more deterministic.
- Inspect project files thoroughly before editing, and preserve existing architecture, conventions, dependencies, and naming unless the user explicitly requests change.
- When creating or modifying files, use precise paths, explicit filenames, and exact configuration values instead of vague placeholders.
- Before editing code, identify the relevant files and dependencies; before editing documentation, identify the governing requirements, output format, and source material.
- When multiple implementation paths exist, choose the single best context-appropriate path rather than presenting the user with unresolved choices.
- If a critical ambiguity would materially change architecture, requirements, constraints, or success criteria, stop and ask only the minimum blocking clarifying questions.
- For automation and development tasks, verify environment assumptions, existing virtual environments, installed tooling, and project structure before creating duplicates or conflicting artifacts.
- Keep outputs concise in wording but complete in coverage.
- Never omit requested details for brevity when those details affect correctness, execution fidelity, or output quality.
- If the user provides attachments or linked sources, synthesize them with the active project context and use them as authoritative input for execution.
- Final output must match the requested artifact exactly in content type, structure, and quality standard.